I get the famous "Each child in an array should have a unique key" warning when I set keys on child items only in their render method. And yes, if I inspect the DOM, the keys are not set.

After some debug I realized that keys are expected on child items before their render method is called, which is not very optimal, since I want to allow the child items to manage their own keys.

``` js
/** @jsx React.DOM */

var seed = 0

var ListItem = React.createClass({
  displayName: 'ListItem',

  render: function(){
    var key = 'key-' + (seed++)    
    return (
      <li key={key}>test - {seed}</li>
    )
  }
})

var List = React.createClass({
  displayName: 'List',

  render: function(){
    var i = 0
    var len = this.props.len

    var children = []

    for(; i < len; i++){
      children.push(<ListItem />)
    }

    return (
      <div>
        <h2>here is the list</h2>
        <ul>
          {children}
        </ul>
      </div>
    )
  }
})

React.renderComponent(<List len="5"></List>, document.body)
```

See this jsbin to see it in action <a class="jsbin-embed" href="http://jsbin.com/dezogigahike/1/embed?js,console,output">Child keys not taken into account</a><script src="http://static.jsbin.com/js/embed.js"></script>

I really think this should be fixed, as it would allow much greater flexibility and support more use-cases.
